Concept and definitions of culture; history and philosophy of culture, Kulturwissenschaft; development of social theory, culture and society (Durkheim, Marx, Weber); approaches to culture in socio-cultural anthropology, main schools (evolutionism, functionalism, structural-functionalism, structural anthropology, interpretive anthropology); sociology of culture (Frankfurt school, Althusser, Gramsci, Bourdieu); macro and micro theories of culture; psychoanalytic approaches to culture (Freud, Jung, Lacan); postmodern and poststructuralist approaches (Baudrillard, Foucault); globalization; psychology of culture (Wundt, Vygotsky); semiotics of culture (Tartu-Moscow school); cultural ecology.Objectives/eesmärkid:  The course provides a general overview of the history and development of the idea of culture in humanities and social sciences, and of different theoretical and methodological approaches to study culture.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  Having graduated from the course a student: 1. is acquainted to main theoretical approaches to culture in the 19th and 20th centuries, to main authors, terms and concepts; 2. recognises the main theoretical and philosophical issues related to defining and studying culture; 3. is independently able to read critically cultural theoretical texts; 4. is able to apply at a preliminary level cultural theoretical ideas and concepts for analysing everyday cultural situations.
